The Box Model: Margin, Padding and Border

- HEIGHT
height: {number}px;

- WIDTH
width: {number}px; 

Can do height and width as a % of total space e.g. height: 80%

- BORDER
If a picture was the image then the border is essentially the picture frame
Border property can take 3 values separated by a space e.g.
border: thickness style colour (style refers to the type of border e.g. solid, dashed, etc)
i.e.
border: 10px solid black;
-> Can further define the border's properties e.g. border-top: 0px
Result: left, right, bottom part of border has thickness 10 px, no top of border (thickness 0px)
e.g. border-width: 0px 10px 20px 30px
    -> Takes 4 inputs because a border is a 4 sided shape, HOWEVER there is an order:
    1st input: top side of border, 2nd input: right side, 3rd input: bottom side, 4th input: left side
    -> Or can give 2 inputs which sets 1&3 as 'a' (top & bottom) and 2&4 as 'b' (right & left)
-> Has to go ON THE NEXT LINE OF WHERE BORDER IS DEFINED

- PADDING
Works the same way as in python; border expands outwards, padding expands inwards 
(essentially pushing the border out by set amount of pixels)
i.e. 
padding: 10px

- MARGIN
Part that's outside of the border; part between border and any other content on the screen
i.e.
margin: 10px

Padding, Margin, Border all work like border-width where you can input 4 values and counts clockwise 
starting from the 1st input being the top

- CONTENT DIVISION ELEMENT
-> If you wanted to wrap multiple elements in the same box, you'd create an artificial box through the 
use of the content division element: <div>Content A Content B Content C etc</div>
-> Pesticide Chrome Extension is a useful tool for debugging because the div elements are invisible
    Once activated, you can see the div boxes show up on screen
